      "author": "Tatyana Benyaguyeva,TXB",
      "text": "Three Empire State Plaza, Albany, NY 12223-1350 www.dps.ny.gov\n\nPublic Service Commission Rory M. Christian Chair and Chief Executive Officer Diane X. Burman James S. Alesi Tracey A. Edwards John B. Howard David J. Valesky John B. Maggiore Commissioners\n\nSeptember 15, 2022\n\nO'Brien, Senator and Nicole The Pandering Pig Restaurant Inc. 209 Pinehurst Avenue, Store New York, NY 10033\n\nJason Justiniano \nConsolidated Edison Company of New York, Inc. \n4 Irving Place \nNew York, New York 10003 \n\nSubject: Informal Hearing Decision Complaint # 011381 Service classification, high electric bill Complaint # 973100 High gas bill\n\nDear Ms. O’Brien and Mr. Justiniano:\n\nAn informal hearing in the case referenced above was held on July 21, 2022. The hearing has been recorded. Ms. O’Brien and Mr. O’Brien represented the complainant, The Pandering Pig Restaurant Inc. (the complainant). Mr. Jason Justiniano represented Consolidated Edison Company of New York, Inc. (Con Edison or the utility). Based on all the information presented, I find that the utility billed the complainant’s account for gas and electric services properly.\n\nBackground\n\nThe complainant is a small restaurant located in Manhattan, New York which has maintained a joint gas and electric account since December 1, 2015. Con Edison bills the complainant for electric service under Service Classification SC 9 1 and for gas under SC\n\n1 Light, heat, and power for general uses where the Customer's initial requirements are expected to be in excess of 10 kilowatts subject to the Common Provisions and Special Provisions of this Service Classification. PSC No. 10, Electricity, Service Classification No. 9 - General Large, Leaf 444, Effective 02/20/2012.\n\n2 2. Billing records show that the first electric bill of $1706.54, issued on February 25, 2016, was for the use of 6912 kWh and the demand of 11.6 kW. After February 25, 2016, the demand exceeded 10 kW every month.\n\nThe complainant contacted the Department of Public Service, the Office of Consumer Services (OCS) on July 19, 2018, regarding the accuracy of electric demand billing. OCS opened a complaint number 829166 and closed it on August 8, 2018, lacking contact from the complainant. The complainant contacted OCS again on September 25, 2018 and requested an electric meter inspection.\n\nOn November 5, 2018, Con Edison visited the complainant’s premises and determined that the initial assignment of Service Classification SC 9 was proper. The utility report of the same date stated the following:\n\nFound no irregular conditions at time of visit. Mr. O’Brien would like meter test.\n\nSubsequently, OCS opened another complaint number 835982. During the investigation OCS requested Staff to perform an electric meter test. On July 18, 2019, Con Edison removed electric meter 71 CM 7837844 3 and installed a new meter A71CM 4779537. DPS Staff tested electric watthour meter number 71 CM 7837844 at 100.1 percent accuracy and the meter’s demand register at 100.05 percent accuracy. The results of both tests were within the accuracy limits prescribed by the Commission 4.\n\nOCS closed complaint 835982 on October 22, 2019, and wrote to the complainant,\n\nPlease be advised that service classification for your business has been determined to be SC 9 because your demand exceed 10 Kw for more than two months. This is the basis for large commercial classification, not for the size of your restaurant. If your demand had remained at 5 Kw or below for a period of 12 months, the service classification would have been assessed as SC 2, a small commercial account.\n\nThe complainant contacted OCS on February 10, 2020 and OCS opened current complaint number 011381. The complainant continued to challenge the assignment of the\n\n2 Any use of gas by any Customer except where the Customer is eligible for service under Service \nClassifications Nos. 1, 3, or 14 subject to the requirements of this Service Classification, the Company's \nSales and Transportation Operating Procedures, and the other applicable provisions of this Rate Schedule, \nprovided however, that religious organizations, community residences that are supportive living facilities or \nsupervised living facilities, and veterans’ posts or halls eligible for service under SC 1 or 3 may elect to take \nservice under this Service Classification. PSC No. 9, Gas, Service Classification No. 2, Leaf 230, Effective \n02/01/2020. \n3 Electric meter 71 CM 7837844 was installed on 07/23/2008. \n4 Meter performance is considered acceptable when the final average accuracy test is not less than 98% \nor greater than 102%. 16 NYCRR Part 92 Operating Manual (7), (e), (iii). The procedures contained in this \noperating manual have been established… for testing and maintaining electricity meters in order to \npromote a high degree of metering performance. \n\nSC 9 service class. They hired Joseph Weinstein Electric Corp. (E-Corp.) to perform a load test. E-Corp. provided a report dated February 8, 2020, stating that the estimated peak of electrical demand was 31,800 watts. On March 11, 2020, Con Edison visited the complainant’s premises to investigate the meters. The utility report of the same date stated the following:\n\nProved above meter 4779537 supplies store. Customer wanted us to do load test for appliances. Informed customers we did not do that, customer provided phone of the load test he had electrician conduct. see attachment. Customers dispute is electric rate 09. Obtain gas rdg of 4393.\n\nThe complainant disagreed with OCS’ determination in this case and requested an informal review.\n\nOn September 09, 2019, the complainant contacted OCS regarding a high gas bill. OCS opened a complaint number 973100. On July 20, 2021, OCS requested a gas meter test. Con Edison reported that they were denied access to the gas meter.\n\nOn February 8, 2022, OCS wrote to the complainant in response to case 973100:\n\nThis is in response to your complaint, Case Number 973100, concerning the difficulty you are experiencing with Con Edison regarding gas usage and billing. You have another Case, 011381 regarding your electric usage and billing. Case 011381 has been referred to our Informal Hearings Unit, as you were dissatisfied with the initial determination rendered by an analyst on my staff. Case 973100 was being investigated and a Public Service Commission Witness Test was to be performed on your gas meter. Con Edison has reported that despite multiple attempts to test the meter, access and removal of the gas meter was refused. A member of the Department of Public Service was on site to oversee the removal, but a letter of authorization was requested, and the technicians and staff member were turned away.\n\nAs this case is almost two years old, and it appears obvious that you do not want the meter removed or tested, we are closing your case. Any monies that are being held in dispute will become collectible by Con Edison in fifteen (15) days from the date of this letter. Should full payment present a hardship, we recommend that you contact the company immediately upon receipt of this letter to determine whether a deferred payment agreement can be negotiated based upon your ability to pay.\n\nWe will inform our Informal Hearings Unit that they may proceed with scheduling the Hearing for Case 011381, as Case 973100 is now closed.\n\nThe complainant was dissatisfied with the outcome of case 973100 and agreed to discuss both gas and electric complaints at an Informal Hearing. 5\n\n5 See complainant’s email to IHO dated 03/18/2021.\n\nDuring the hearing the complainant requested a gas meter test. On August 26, 2022, Con Edison removed the gas meter for testing. On August 29, 2022, OCS Staff tested the gas meter at 98.2 percent accuracy, which is within the accuracy limits established by the Commission. 6\n\nComplainant’s Position\n\nThe complainant stated the following on February 25, 2020,\n\nDear Honorable Governor Cuomo,\n\nI am a 47-year-old business owner and a mother of three. I am the chef of my small ",
